: State[] $[rws]
- Modifier applies to var (array can be reassigned) and array elements (array elements can be modified)

: State&[] $[*rw]
- Modifier applies to the `State` objects whose references are stored in the array
 - The array cannot be reassigned, the array elements (refererence pointers) cannot be reassigned
 - The objects pointed to by the array elements can be modified

: State[]& $[*rw]
- Modifier applies to the array referenced by the `State[]&` pointer (the State[] array)
 - This is equivalent to a pointer to the object in the first example

: State&[]& $[*rw]
- Modifier applies to the referenced `State&[]` array.
 - Equivalent to the above example except the referenced array is of type `State&[]` and not `State[]`

: State&[]& $[**rw]
- Dereferences on modifiers "fall through" any arrays, so this applies the modifier to the `State` objects referenced by the array elements

: State[][] $[rw]
- Array dimensions cannot be individually protected so this is the same as the first example, just with a 2d array

: State&[]&[]& $[**rw]
- This is a "pointer to array of pointer to array of pointer to State"
- Again, modifier dereferences "fall through" any arrays so this dereferences two of the "pointer to" above
 - This results in rw access on the `State&[]` parts of this data